STRDUP(3)                   Linux Programmer's Manual                  STRDUP(3)

NNAAMMEE
       strdup, strndup, strdupa, strndupa - duplicate a string

SSYYNNOOPPSSIISS
       ##iinncclluuddee <<ssttrriinngg..hh>>

       cchhaarr **ssttrrdduupp((ccoonnsstt cchhaarr **_s));;

       cchhaarr **ssttrrnndduupp((ccoonnsstt cchhaarr **_s,, ssiizzee__tt _n));;
       cchhaarr **ssttrrdduuppaa((ccoonnsstt cchhaarr **_s));;
       cchhaarr **ssttrrnndduuppaa((ccoonnsstt cchhaarr **_s,, ssiizzee__tt _n));;

   Feature Test Macro Requirements for glibc (see ffeeaattuurree__tteesstt__mmaaccrrooss(7)):

       ssttrrdduupp():
           _XOPEN_SOURCE >= 500
               || /* Since glibc 2.12: */ _POSIX_C_SOURCE >= 200809L
               || /* Glibc versions <= 2.19: */ _BSD_SOURCE || _SVID_SOURCE
       ssttrrnndduupp():
           Since glibc 2.10:
               _POSIX_C_SOURCE >= 200809L
           Before glibc 2.10:
               _GNU_SOURCE
       ssttrrdduuppaa(), ssttrrnndduuppaa(): _GNU_SOURCE

DDEESSCCRRIIPPTTIIOONN
       The ssttrrdduupp() function returns a pointer to a new string which is a dupli‐
       cate of the string _s.  Memory for the new string is  obtained  with  mmaall‐‐
       lloocc(3), and can be freed with ffrreeee(3).

       The  ssttrrnndduupp()  function is similar, but copies at most _n bytes.  If _s is
       longer than _n, only _n bytes are  copied,  and  a  terminating  null  byte
       ('\0') is added.

       ssttrrdduuppaa()  and  ssttrrnndduuppaa() are similar, but use aallllooccaa(3) to allocate the
       buffer.  They are available only when using the GNU GCC suite, and suffer
       from the same limitations described in aallllooccaa(3).

RREETTUURRNN VVAALLUUEE
       On  success,  the  ssttrrdduupp()  function returns a pointer to the duplicated
       string.  It returns NULL if insufficient memory was available, with _e_r_r_n_o
       set to indicate the cause of the error.

EERRRROORRSS
       EENNOOMMEEMM Insufficient memory available to allocate duplicate string.

AATTTTRRIIBBUUTTEESS
       For an explanation of the terms used in this section, see aattttrriibbuutteess(7).

       ┌────────────────────────────────┬───────────────┬─────────┐
       │IInntteerrffaaccee                       │ AAttttrriibbuuttee     │ VVaalluuee   │
       ├────────────────────────────────┼───────────────┼─────────┤
       │ssttrrdduupp(), ssttrrnndduupp(), ssttrrdduuppaa(), │ Thread safety │ MT-Safe │
       │ssttrrnndduuppaa()                      │               │         │
       └────────────────────────────────┴───────────────┴─────────┘

CCOONNFFOORRMMIINNGG TTOO
       ssttrrdduupp()  conforms  to SVr4, 4.3BSD, POSIX.1-2001.  ssttrrnndduupp() conforms to
       POSIX.1-2008.  ssttrrdduuppaa() and ssttrrnndduuppaa() are GNU extensions.

SSEEEE AALLSSOO
       aallllooccaa(3), ccaalllloocc(3), ffrreeee(3),  mmaalllloocc(3),  rreeaalllloocc(3),  ssttrriinngg(3),  wwccss‐‐
       dduupp(3)

